‚úÖ Step 2: Import Libraries in Python
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score

Simple Explanation:

Pandas ‚Üí handling dataset

NumPy ‚Üí numerical calculations

Matplotlib & Seaborn ‚Üí graphs

Scikit-learn ‚Üí machine learning model

Metrics ‚Üí check model performance

‚úÖ Step 3: Load Your Dataset

If dataset file is customers.csv:

df = pd.read_csv("customers.csv")
df.head()

Simple Explanation:

Loads the dataset and shows first 5 rows.

‚úÖ Step 4: Explore The Data (EDA)
df.info()
df.describe()

Check correlation
sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, cmap="coolwarm")
plt.show()

Simple Explanation:

This step helps you understand:

Which column is related to which

Which features strongly affect yearly spending

‚úÖ Step 5: Visualize Relationships
sns.pairplot(df)
plt.show()

Simple Explanation:

Pairplot shows the relation of each feature vs spending.

‚úÖ Step 6: Select Features (X) and Target (y)
X = df[['Avg. Session Length', 'Time on App', 'Time on Website', 'Length of Membership']]
y = df['Yearly Amount Spent']

Simple Explanation:

X ‚Üí input features

y ‚Üí predicted value (spending)

‚úÖ Step 7: Split Train & Test Data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42
)

Simple Explanation:

70% data ‚Üí train model

30% data ‚Üí test model

‚úÖ Step 8: Train the Linear Regression Model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

Simple Explanation:

Model learns the relationship between features and spending.

‚úÖ Step 9: Check Model Coefficients
print("Intercept:", model.intercept_)
print("Coefficients:", model.coef_)

Simple Explanation:

Coefficients tell how much a feature affects spending.
Example:
If Length of Membership coefficient = 35,
‚Üí Every extra 1 year membership increases spending by ‚Çπ35.

‚úÖ Step 10: Predict on Test Set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

‚úÖ Step 11: Evaluate the Model
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

print("MAE:", mae)
print("MSE:", mse)
print("RMSE:", rmse)
print("R¬≤ Score:", r2)

Simple Explanation:

MAE ‚Üí Average error

MSE ‚Üí Squared error

RMSE ‚Üí Root mean squared error

R¬≤ ‚Üí How well model fits the data (1 = perfect)

‚úÖ Step 12: Plot Actual vs Predicted
plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred)
plt.xlabel("Actual Spending")
plt.ylabel("Predicted Spending")
plt.title("Actual vs Predicted")
plt.show()

Simple Explanation:

If dots lie near a straight line ‚Üí model is good.

üéâ Your Project Is Ready!

This is a complete end-to-end machine learning project.

‚≠ê Full Project Code (Copy‚ÄìPaste)
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, mean_absolute_error, r2_score

df = pd.read_csv("customers.csv")
print(df.head())

# EDA
print(df.info())
print(df.describe())

sns.heatmap(df.corr(), annot=True, cmap="coolwarm")
plt.show()

sns.pairplot(df)
plt.show()

# Features & Target
X = df[['Avg. Session Length', 'Time on App', 'Time on Website', 'Length of Membership']]
y = df['Yearly Amount Spent']

# Split data
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.3, random_state=42
)

# Train model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Coefficients
print("Intercept:", model.intercept_)
print("Coefficients:", model.coef_)

# Predict
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluation
mae = mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred)
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mse)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)

print("MAE:", mae)
print("MSE:", mse)
print("RMSE:", rmse)
print("R¬≤ Score:", r2)

# Plot
plt.scatter(y_test, y_pred)
plt.xlabel("Actual Spending")
plt.ylabel("Predicted Spending")
plt.title("Actual vs Predicted")
plt.show()





‚úÖ 6-Line Project Summary (Perfect for Interviews)

"I built a Customer Spending Prediction model using Multiple Linear Regression to understand how user behavior impacts yearly spending. I first performed EDA using Pandas, Seaborn, and correlation heatmaps to identify which features‚Äîlike Avg Session Length, Time on App, Time on Website, and Length of Membership‚Äîare most related to spending. I then prepared the data and trained a LinearRegression model from scikit-learn using a train-test split. After training, I evaluated the model using R¬≤, MAE, MSE, and RMSE to check accuracy. I also analyzed the model coefficients to understand the business impact of each feature, where Length of Membership came out strongest. Finally, I plotted Actual vs Predicted values to visually validate the model and generated insights to help improve app engagement and customer retention."
